cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this skill or any perspective skill generated by it in your research or writing, please cite it as below."
type: software
title: "Scholar-Wendao: A Framework for Distilling Scholar Perspectives into Runnable Analytical Lenses"
version: 0.6.3
date-released: 2026-05-19
authors:
  - family-names: Shen
    given-names: Cong
    alias: tizzy916
    affiliation: "Tianyu Vision (TIANYU VISION); MA, History of Science, Tsinghua University"
    website: "https://tianyu.art/"
abstract: >
  An open-source framework for distilling scholar perspectives into runnable
  analytical lenses for humanities researchers. Input a scholar's name or
  research area; the framework automatically harvests multilingual works,
  secondary literature, biographies, and academic controversies, then
  produces a "perspective skill" — a portable analytical lens you can
  invoke in your research workflow rather than a chatbot to converse with.
  Supports two scholar types: contemporary (single-author, e.g., Stiegler,
  Yuk Hui) and traditional (multi-reception lineages, e.g., Aristotle,
  Plato, Confucius). Traditional-scholar mode produces multi-perspective
  output showing how each interpretive lineage reads the source. Designed
  for humanities-paper writing workflows — not for casual chat or persona
  role-play. Methodology inspired by Huashu's nuwa-skill, redesigned for
  academic humanities use. Bilingual: documentation in English and Chinese.
keywords:
